I hardly ever talk about games on here but i feel like this one needs some more love, is all. Since it does go on sale LUDICROUSLY OFTEN (at least on Switch) next time you see it for sale please please consider it.

Oh also the characters, oh my god the characters! They have...well, so much character, for lack of a better word. And the backstories....my goodness. I’ve cried at least a few times, and been so moved by quite a few of them.

6- I don’t WANT to finish it, even though the grind is real now and real annoying, because then it would be over. So far i give this an 11/11. *i only said it was old bc iirc it’s a year old and that is ancient in the current game landscape.

5- leading to A LOT of back and forth grinding/hunting for resources.  And the game could be A LOT clearer about certain things, esp later on. All that said- This game has consumed me, i play it to the detriment of anything else, and when i’m not i’m thinking about it.

4- Does it have flaws? Of course! Not least of which is - the gameplay does tend to get repetitive, fetch quests do tend to get tedious, the cooking *really* needed to be sped up, and most annoyingly, late middle to early late game, things tend to get money/material gated

3/?- But to me the fact that, at least on the switch, you can get this for $25 regular and on sale (FREQUENTLY on sale at that) for $15, is a goddamn travesty. This game could have and should have been priced better.

1/?- It’s Just That Good, imo. I certainly would have paid $50-$60 for it. Granted i feel like you need to drop a demo for this game that’s a few hours long beforehand, just so people can know what they’re getting.

Been thinking about all that lately. I mean obviously i think about the people too, but for so many of those folks their horses *were* their family...

But that despite all the hardship, that when there was a show, *Everyone* showed up, and celebrated the horses. It didn’t matter where you were from, you were there for the horses and because you loved the horses.
But the guards wouldn’t let them cross, despite having the vet on the phone saying they had to. So their horse died.
Because if something goes wrong, Palestine doesn’t have its own Equine Vet, so they have to call the one in Israel. And one time a family’s horse needed the hospital so they had to cross the border.

Anyway been thinking lately about that doc and how you learn how there’s such a huge culture of horse rearing in Palestine. Every family has a horse, or had one at some point or knew someone who did. And how it’s really hard to breed them or just own them in Palestine

This is all to say that it's nothing I can't cope with, just that I wish I didn't have to.
Which is when it happens. Woke up this morning with no blankets, within...les than an hour I got that awful feeling.

I have traced back the source of it to a few things which I can control and literally one I can't. Ginger ale, and eating after 7pm. Don't eat after 7pm, have my last ginger ale AT LEAST 2 hours before I go to bed. But I legit can't control if I kick the covers off and get cold.
No doctor I've seen seems to know what it really is or how to treat it, other than tossing inhalers at me. But you can only go so high on the dosage of those.

Hard but doable in spring and early summer. Nigh on impossible to do now. Oh, and if none of those work- because they sometimes don't- just...waiting it out. Sometimes it goes away in 3 hours, sometimes....close to 9, is the longest I've had it.

The only remedy I've found is- drink tea, sit up absolutely straight (sucks when you get it when you're sleeping tbh, since it wakes you up then and sleeping is impossible with it) pile. On. The layers. I'm talking sweaters, pants, hat, scarf and gloves.

I hate that I seem to have the one type of asthma that inhalers *dont* help. It's set off by coldness, and being *too* cold, but since knowing HOW cold is "too" would be helpful, naturally I don't know that.
